 debounce.js
```javascript
// debounce: A utility function to limit the rate at which a function is called, by only allowing it to be called once per every 'wait' milliseconds.

function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;

  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => {
      func(...args);
    }, wait);
  };
}

// Usage example:

const log = console.log;

const debouncedLog = debounce(log, 1000);

setInterval(() => {
  debouncedLog('Hello, debounced world!');
}, 500);
```

In this example, we create a debounce function that takes a function `func` and a wait time in milliseconds `wait`. It returns a new function that, when called, will clear any pending timeouts and schedules a new one to call the original function `func` after `wait` milliseconds. We then create a debounced version of `console.log` called `debouncedLog` with a 1000ms wait time. Inside an interval that runs every 500ms, we call `debouncedLog` with a log message. The output will be "Hello, debounced world!" every second, instead of every half second, because the debounce function rate-limits the calls to `console.log`.
